<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Production">Production</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DThe_Matrix&amp;a=
ction=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Production"><span>edit=
</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Development">Development</h=
3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DThe_Matrix&amp=
;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Development"><span>e=
dit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In 1994, the Wachowskis presented the script for the film <i><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Assassins_(1995_film)" title=3D"Assassins (19=
95 film)">Assassins</a></i> to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War=
ner_Bros._Pictures" title=3D"Warner Bros. Pictures">Warner Bros. Pictures</=
a>. After <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lorenzo_di_Bonaventura" =
title=3D"Lorenzo di Bonaventura">Lorenzo di Bonaventura</a>, the president =
of production of the company at the time, read the script, he decided to bu=
y rights to it and included two more pictures, <i><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Bound_(1996_film)" title=3D"Bound (1996 film)">Bound</a></i=
> and <i>The Matrix</i>, in the contract. The first movie the Wachowskis di=
rected, <i>Bound</i>, then became a critical success. Using this momentum, =
they later asked to direct <i>The Matrix</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Influence_=
Screened_33-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/The_Matrix#cite_note-Influence_Screened-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Reeves said that t=
he Matrix avatar would have been a "different sex than the Zion reality" in=
 the early draft of the script, but the studio was not ready for that versi=
on.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-34" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-34"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In 1996, the Wachowskis pitched the role of Neo to <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Will_Smith" title=3D"Will Smith">Will Smith</a>. Sm=
ith explained on his <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/YouTube" titl=
e=3D"YouTube">YouTube</a> channel that the idea was for him to be Neo, whil=
e Morpheus was to be played by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Val=
_Kilmer" title=3D"Val Kilmer">Val Kilmer</a>. He later explained that he di=
d not quite understand the concept and he turned down the role to instead f=
ilm <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wild_Wild_West" title=3D"Wi=
ld Wild West">Wild Wild West</a></i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-35" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-35"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Madonna" title=3D"Madonna=
">Madonna</a> also turned down an undisclosed role, a decision she would la=
ter regret.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-36" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-36"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Producer <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joel_Silver" title=
=3D"Joel Silver">Joel Silver</a> soon joined the project. Although the proj=
ect had key supporters, including Silver and Di Bonaventura, to influence t=
he company, <i>The Matrix</i> was still a huge investment for Warner Bros.,=
 which had to invest $60 million to create a movie with prominent actors an=
d difficult special effects.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Influence_Screened_33-1" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_=
note-Influence_Screened-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>32<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The Wachowskis therefore hired unde=
rground comic book artists <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geof_Da=
rrow" title=3D"Geof Darrow">Geof Darrow</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Steve_Skroce" title=3D"Steve Skroce">Steve Skroce</a> to draw=
 a 600-page, shot-by-shot storyboard for the entire film.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-37" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matr=
ix#cite_note-37"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>36<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-38" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-38"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>37<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-39" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-39"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>38<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The storyboard eventually ea=
rned the studio's approval, and it was decided to film in Australia to make=
 the most of the budget.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Influence_Screened_33-2" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_not=
e-Influence_Screened-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>32<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Soon, <i>The Matrix</i> became a co-pr=
oduction of Warner Bros. and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Villa=
ge_Roadshow_Pictures" title=3D"Village Roadshow Pictures">Village Roadshow =
Pictures</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Museum_40-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-Museum-40"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>39<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> According to editor <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zach_Staenb=
erg" title=3D"Zach Staenberg">Zach Staenberg</a> on the DVD audio commentar=
y track, the production team sent an edit of the film's first minutes (feat=
uring Trinity's encounter with police and Agents) to Warner Bros. executive=
s, and secured Warner Bros.' "total support of the movie" from then on.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-41" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-41"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>40<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Pre-production">Pre-product=
ion</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DThe_Matr=
ix&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Pre-production=
"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></spa=
n></div>
<p>The cast were required to be able to understand and explain <i>The Matri=
x</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Influence_Screened_33-3" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-Influence_Screene=
d-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> French philosopher <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Jean_Baudrillard" title=3D"Jean Baudrillard">Jean Baudrillard</a>'s <i><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simulacra_and_Simulation" title=3D"=
Simulacra and Simulation">Simulacra and Simulation</a></i> was required rea=
ding for most of the principal cast and crew.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Simulacra_=
42-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matr=
ix#cite_note-Simulacra-42"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>41<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In early 1997, the Wachowskis had Re=
eves and Moss read <i>Simulacra and Simulation</i>, <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Kevin_Kelly_(editor)" title=3D"Kevin Kelly (editor)">Kevi=
n Kelly</a>'s <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Out_of_Control:_T=
he_New_Biology_of_Machines,_Social_Systems,_and_the_Economic_World" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Out of Control: The New Biology of Machines, Soci=
al Systems, and the Economic World">Out of Control: The New Biology of Mach=
ines, Social Systems, and the Economic World</a></i>, and <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dylan_Evans" title=3D"Dylan Evans">Dylan Evans</a>'=
s ideas on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Evolutionary_psychology=
" title=3D"Evolutionary psychology">evolutionary psychology</a> even before=
 they opened up the script.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Screenplay_13-3" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-Scre=
enplay-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup> Eventually, Reeves was able to explain all the philo=
sophical nuances involved.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Influence_Screened_33-4" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_no=
te-Influence_Screened-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>32<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Moss commented that she had difficult=
y with this process.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Screenplay_13-4" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-Screenplay-=
13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup>
</p><p>The directors had long been admirers of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Hong_Kong_action_cinema" title=3D"Hong Kong action cinema">Hon=
g Kong action cinema</a>, so they decided to hire the Chinese <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fight_choreography" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Fight choreography">martial arts choreographer</a> and film director <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yuen_Woo-ping" title=3D"Yuen Woo-pin=
g">Yuen Woo-ping</a> to work on fight scenes. To prepare for the <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wire_fu" title=3D"Wire fu">wire fu</a>, the =
actors had to train hard for several months.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Influence_S=
creened_33-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
The_Matrix#cite_note-Influence_Screened-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The Wachowskis firs=
t scheduled four months for training, beginning in October 1997.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-43" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/T=
he_Matrix#cite_note-43"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>42<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Yuen was optimistic but then began to =
worry when he realized how unfit the actors were.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Traini=
ng_22-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_M=
atrix#cite_note-Training-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Yuen let their body style develop and then worked with each actor's =
strength. He built on Reeves's diligence, Fishburne's resilience, Weaving's=
 precision and Moss's grace.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Training_22-2" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-Train=
ing-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup> Yuen designed Moss's moves to suit her deftness and lig=
htness.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Trinity_44-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-Trinity-44"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>43<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Pri=
or to the pre-production, Reeves underwent a two-level fusion of his cervic=
al (neck) spine due to spinal cord compression from a herniated disc ("I wa=
s falling over in the shower in the morning").<sup id=3D"cite_ref-45" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_not=
e-45"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>44<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> He was still recovering by the time of pre-production, bu=
t he insisted on training, so Yuen let him practice punches and lighter mov=
es. Reeves trained hard and even requested training on days off. However, t=
he surgery still made him unable to kick for two out of four months of trai=
ning. As a result, Reeves did not kick much in the film.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-Training_22-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/The_Matrix#cite_note-Training-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-46" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_no=
te-46"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>45<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup> Weaving had to undergo <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Hip_replacement" title=3D"Hip replacement">hip surgery</a> after he=
 sustained an injury during the training process.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Influe=
nce_Screened_33-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-Influence_Screened-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Filming">Filming</h3><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DThe_Matrix&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Filming"><span>edit</span><=
/a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Campbell_Street_train_bridge_at_intersection_=
of_Elizabeth_Street.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://=
upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/86/Campbell_Street_train_bri=
dge_at_intersection_of_Elizabeth_Street.jpg/250px-Campbell_Street_train_bri=
dge_at_intersection_of_Elizabeth_Street.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"25=
0" height=3D"141" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"4032" data-f=
ile-height=3D"2268"></a><figcaption>Campbell Street train bridge at the int=
ersection of Elizabeth Street was one of the filming locations in the city =
of Sydney.</figcaption></figure>
<p>All but a few scenes were filmed at <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Fox_Studios_Australia" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Fox Studios Aust=
ralia">Fox Studios</a> in Sydney, as well as in the city itself, although r=
ecognizable landmarks were not included to maintain the impression of a gen=
eric American city. The filming helped establish <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/New_South_Wales" title=3D"New South Wales">New South Wales</=
a> as a major film production center.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-47" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-47"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>46<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-48" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-48"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>47<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Filming began in Mar=
ch 1998 and wrapped in August 1998; <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Principal_photography" title=3D"Principal photography">principal photogra=
phy</a> took 118 days.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-The_Power_Plant_49-0" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-The_=
Power_Plant-49"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>48<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> Some filming also occurred at <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Culver_Studios" title=3D"Culver Studios">Culver Stu=
dios</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-50" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-50"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>49<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Due to Reeves's neck injury (see above), some of the action scenes h=
ad to be rescheduled to wait for his full recovery. As a result, the filmin=
g began with scenes that did not require much physical exertion,<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-The_Shooting_Begins_51-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-The_Shooting_Begins-51"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>50<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p><sup id=3D"cite_ref-52" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-52"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5=
1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> such as the scene in Thoma=
s Anderson's office, the interrogation room,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Interrogati=
on_Room_31-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
The_Matrix#cite_note-Interrogation_Room-31"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> or the car ride in =
which Neo is taken to see the Oracle.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Car_Ride_to_the_Or=
acle_53-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The=
_Matrix#cite_note-Car_Ride_to_the_Oracle-53"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>52<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Locations for thes=
e scenes included <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Martin_Place,_Sy=
dney" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Martin Place, Sydney">Martin Place's</=
a> fountain in Sydney, halfway between it and the adjacent Colonial Buildin=
g, and the Colonial Building itself.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-CNN_location_54-0" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cit=
e_note-CNN_location-54"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>53<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> During the scene set on a government b=
uilding rooftop, the team filmed extra footage of Neo dodging bullets in ca=
se the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bullet_time" title=3D"Bulle=
t time">bullet time</a> process did not work. The bullet-time fight scene w=
as filmed on the roof of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NortonLif=
eLock" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"NortonLifeLock">Symantec</a> Corporat=
ion building in Kent Street, opposite <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Sussex_Street,_Sydney" title=3D"Sussex Street, Sydney">Sussex Street</a=
>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Government_Roof_55-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-Government_Roof-55"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>54<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup>
</p><p>Moss performed the shots featuring Trinity at the beginning of the f=
ilm and all the wire stunts herself.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Trinity_44-1" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_not=
e-Trinity-44"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>43<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup> The rooftop set that Trinity uses to escape from =
Agent Brown early in the film was left over from the production of <i><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dark_City_(1998_film)" title=3D"Dark Ci=
ty (1998 film)">Dark City</a></i>, which has prompted comments due to the t=
hematic similarities of the films.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-56" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-56"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>55<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> During the rehearsal of the lobby scene, in which Trinity runs on a w=
all, Moss injured her leg and was ultimately unable to film the shot in one=
 take. She stated that she was under a lot of pressure at the time and was =
devastated when she realized that she would be unable to do it.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-Government_Lobby_57-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-Government_Lobby-57"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>56<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/D%C5%8Dj%C5%8D" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"D=C5=8Dj=C5=8D">dojo</a> set was built well befor=
e the actual filming. During the filming of these action sequences, there w=
as significant physical contact between the actors, earning them bruises. R=
eeves's injury and his insufficient training with wires prior to filming me=
ant he was unable to perform the triple kicks satisfactorily and became fru=
strated with himself, causing the scene to be postponed. The scene was shot=
 successfully a few days later, with Reeves using only three takes. Yuen al=
tered the choreography and made the actors pull their punches in the last s=
equence of the scene, creating a training feel.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Construc=
t_Kung_Fu_58-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/The_Matrix#cite_note-Construct_Kung_Fu-58"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>57<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The filmmakers originally planned to shoot the subway scene in an ac=
tual <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metro_station" title=3D"Metro=
 station">subway station</a>, but the complexity of the fight and related w=
ire work required shooting the scene on a set. The set was built around an =
existing train storage facility, which had real train tracks. Filming the s=
cene when Neo slammed Smith into the ceiling, <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Chad_Stahelski" title=3D"Chad Stahelski">Chad Stahelski</a>, Re=
eves's stunt double, sustained several injuries, including <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rib_fracture" title=3D"Rib fracture">broken ribs</=
a>, knees and a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dislocated_shoulde=
r" title=3D"Dislocated shoulder">dislocated shoulder</a>. Another stuntman =
was injured by a hydraulic puller during a shot in which Neo was slammed in=
to a booth.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-El_Fighting_59-0" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-El_Fighting-59"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>58<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> The office building in which Smith interrogated Morpheus was a lar=
ge set, and the outside view from inside the building was a large, three st=
ory high <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cyclorama" title=3D"Cyclo=
rama">cyclorama</a>. The helicopter was a full-scale, light-weight mock-up =
suspended by a wire rope operated a tilting mechanism mounted to the studio=
 roofbeams. The helicopter had a real minigun side-mounted to it, which was=
 set to cycle at half its regular (3,000 rounds per minute) firing rate.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-Helicopter_Rescue_60-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-Helicopter_Rescue-60"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>59<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup>
</p><p>To prepare for the scene in which Neo wakes up in a pod, Reeves lost=
 15 pounds (7&nbsp;kg) and shaved his whole body to give Neo an emaciated l=
ook. The scene in which Neo fell into the sewer system concluded the princi=
pal photography.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-The_Power_Plant_49-1" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-The_Power_=
Plant-49"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>48<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup> According to <i>The Art of the Matrix</i>, at least o=
ne filmed scene and a variety of short pieces of action were omitted from t=
he final cut of the film.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-61" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-61"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>60<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Sound_effects_and_music">So=
und effects and music</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.ph=
p?title=3DThe_Matrix&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit secti=
on: Sound effects and music"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsec=
tion-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix:_Original_Mot=
ion_Picture_Score" title=3D"The Matrix: Original Motion Picture Score">The =
Matrix: Original Motion Picture Score</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/The_Matrix:_Music_from_the_Motion_Picture" title=3D"The Matrix:=
 Music from the Motion Picture">The Matrix: Music from the Motion Picture</=
a></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dane_A._Davis" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"Dane A. Davis">Dane A. Davis</a> was responsible for creatin=
g the sound effects for the film. The fight scene sound effects, such as th=
e whipping sounds of punches, were created using thin metal rods and record=
ing them, then editing the sounds. The sound of the pod containing a human =
body closing required almost fifty sounds put together.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
Sound_effects_62-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-Sound_effects-62"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>61<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The film's <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Film_score" titl=
e=3D"Film score">score</a>, <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The=
_Matrix:_Original_Motion_Picture_Score" title=3D"The Matrix: Original Motio=
n Picture Score">The Matrix: Original Motion Picture Score</a></i>, was com=
posed by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Don_Davis_(composer)" tit=
le=3D"Don Davis (composer)">Don Davis</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-63" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-63=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>62<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-64" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-64"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>63<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> He noted that m=
irrors appear frequently in the film: reflections of the blue and red pills=
 are seen in Morpheus's glasses; Neo's capture by Agents is viewed through =
the rear-view mirror of Trinity's motorcycle; Neo observes a broken mirror =
mending itself; reflections warp as a spoon is bent; the reflection of a he=
licopter is visible as it approaches a skyscraper. Davis focused on this th=
eme of reflections when creating his score, alternating between sections of=
 the orchestra and attempting to incorporate <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Counterpoint" title=3D"Counterpoint">contrapuntal</a> ideas. Dav=
is' score combines orchestral, choral and synthesizer elements; the balance=
 between these elements varies depending on whether humans or machines are =
the dominant subject of a given scene.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-The_Score_65-0" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite=
_note-The_Score-65"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>64<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
In addition to Davis' score, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_M=
atrix:_Music_from_the_Motion_Picture" title=3D"The Matrix: Music from the M=
otion Picture">The Matrix: Music from the Motion Picture</a> also features =
music from acts such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rammstein"=
 title=3D"Rammstein">Rammstein</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Rob_Dougan" title=3D"Rob Dougan">Rob Dougan</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Rage_Against_the_Machine" title=3D"Rage Against the Machin=
e">Rage Against the Machine</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P=
ropellerheads" title=3D"Propellerheads">Propellerheads</a>, <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ministry_(band)" title=3D"Ministry (band)">Minist=
ry</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lunatic_Calm" title=3D"Lun=
atic Calm">Lunatic Calm</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Defto=
nes" title=3D"Deftones">Deftones</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Monster_Magnet" title=3D"Monster Magnet">Monster Magnet</a>, <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Prodigy" title=3D"The Prodigy">The Prodi=
gy</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rob_Zombie" title=3D"Rob Z=
ombie">Rob Zombie</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meat_Beat_M=
anifesto" title=3D"Meat Beat Manifesto">Meat Beat Manifesto</a> and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marilyn_Manson_(band)" title=3D"Marilyn M=
anson (band)">Marilyn Manson</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-66" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-66"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>65<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-67" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-67"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>66<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-68" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite=
_note-68"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>67<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Production_design">Producti=
on design</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DTh=
e_Matrix&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: Producti=
on design"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</s=
pan></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix_digital_rain" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Matrix digital rain">Matrix digital rain</a></d=
iv>
<p>In the film, the code that composes the Matrix itself is frequently repr=
esented as downward-flowing green characters.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-69" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_not=
e-69"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>68<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> This code uses a custom typeface designed by Simon Whitel=
ey,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Museum_40-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-Museum-40"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>39<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> which inc=
ludes mirror images of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Half-width_=
kana" title=3D"Half-width kana">half-width kana</a> characters and Western =
Latin letters and Arabic numerals.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Look_of_the_Matrix_70=
-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix=
#cite_note-Look_of_the_Matrix-70"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>69<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In a 2017 interview at <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CNET" title=3D"CNET">CNET</a>, he attrib=
uted the design to his wife, who is from Japan, and added, "I like to tell =
everybody that The Matrix's code is made out of Japanese sushi recipes".<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-71" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-71"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>70<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> "The color green reflects the g=
reen tint commonly used on early <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M=
onochrome_monitor" title=3D"Monochrome monitor">monochrome computer monitor=
s</a>".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-72" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-72"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>71<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Lynne Cartwright, the=
 Visual Effects Supervisor at <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anim=
al_Logic" title=3D"Animal Logic">Animal Logic</a>, supervised the creation =
of the film's opening title sequence, as well as the general look of the Ma=
trix code throughout the film, in collaboration with Lindsay Fleay and Just=
en Marshall.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Museum_40-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-Museum-40"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>39<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 The portrayal resembles the opening credits of the 1995 <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Japanese_cyberpunk" title=3D"Japanese cyberpunk">Jap=
anese cyberpunk</a> film, <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ghost=
_in_the_Shell_(1995_film)" title=3D"Ghost in the Shell (1995 film)">Ghost i=
n the Shell</a></i>, which had a strong influence on the <i>Matrix</i> seri=
es. It was also used in the subsequent films, on the related website, and i=
n the game <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix:_Path_of_=
Neo" title=3D"The Matrix: Path of Neo">The Matrix: Path of Neo</a></i>, and=
 its drop-down effect is reflected in the design of some posters for the <i=
>Matrix</i> series. The code received the Runner-up Award in the 1999 Jesse=
 Garson Award for In-film typography or opening credit sequence.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-Museum_40-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-Museum-40"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>39<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><i>The Matrix</i><span class=3D"nowrap" style=3D"padding-left:0.1em;=
">'</span>s <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Production_design" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Production design">production designer</a>, <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Owen_Paterson_(production_designer)" =
title=3D"Owen Paterson (production designer)">Owen Paterson</a>, used metho=
ds to distinguish the "real world" and the Matrix in a pervasive way. The p=
roduction design team generally placed a bias towards the Matrix code's dis=
tinctive green color in scenes set within the simulation, whereas there is =
an emphasis on the color blue during scenes set in the "real world". In add=
ition, the Matrix scenes' sets were slightly more decayed, monolithic and g=
rid-like, to convey the cold, logical and artificial nature of that environ=
ment. For the "real world", the actors' hair was less styled, their clothin=
g had more textile content, and the cinematographers used longer lenses to =
soften the backgrounds and emphasize the actors.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Look_of=
_the_Matrix_70-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/The_Matrix#cite_note-Look_of_the_Matrix-70"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>69<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nebuchadnezzar_(The_=
Matrix)" title=3D"Nebuchadnezzar (The Matrix)">Nebuchadnezzar</a></i> was d=
esigned to have a patched-up look, instead of clean, cold and sterile space=
 ship interior sets as used on productions such as <i><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Star_Trek" title=3D"Star Trek">Star Trek</a></i>. The w=
ires were made visible to show the ship's working internals, and each compo=
sition was carefully designed to convey the ship as "a marriage between Man=
 and Machine".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-The_Nebuchadnezzar_73-0" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-The_Nebuc=
hadnezzar-73"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>72<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup> For the scene when Neo wakes up in the pod connec=
ted to the Matrix, the pod was constructed to look dirty, used and sinister=
. During the testing of a breathing mechanism in the pod, the tester suffer=
ed hypothermia in under eight minutes, so the pod had to be heated.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-The_Power_Plant_49-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-The_Power_Plant-49"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>48<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kym_Barrett" title=3D"Kym B=
arrett">Kym Barrett</a>, costume designer, said that she defined the charac=
ters and their environment by their costume.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Costume_74-=
0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#=
cite_note-Costume-74"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>73<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For example, Reeves's office costume was =
designed for Thomas Anderson to look uncomfortable, disheveled and out of p=
lace.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-The_Shooting_Begins_51-1" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-The_Shooting_Begi=
ns-51"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>50<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup> Barrett sometimes used three types of fabric for each co=
stume, and also had to consider the practicality of the acting. The actors =
needed to perform martial art actions in their costume, hang upside-down wi=
thout people seeing up their clothing, and be able to work the wires while =
strapped into the harnesses.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Costume_74-1" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-Costum=
e-74"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>73<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> For Trinity, Barrett experimented with how each fabric ab=
sorbed and reflected different types of light, and was eventually able to m=
ake Trinity's costume mercury-like and oil-slick to suit the character.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-Trinity_44-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-Trinity-44"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>43<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For the Agents=
, their costume was designed to create a secret service, undercover look, r=
esembling the film <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/JFK_(film)" =
title=3D"JFK (film)">JFK</a></i> and classic <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Men_in_black" title=3D"Men in black">men in black</a>.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-Interrogation_Room_31-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-Interrogation_Room-31"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>
</p><p>The sunglasses, a staple of the film's aesthetics, were commissioned=
 for the film by designer Richard Walker from sunglasses maker Blinde Desig=
n.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-75" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-75"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7=
4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Visual_effects">Visual effe=
cts</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DThe_Matr=
ix&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit section: Visual effects=
"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></spa=
n></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><span><span clas=
s=3D"mw-tmh-player video"><video id=3D"mwe_player_0_placeholder" poster=3D"=
https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/3/31/The_Matrix_Bullet_Time=
_Effect.ogv/250px--The_Matrix_Bullet_Time_Effect.ogv.jpg" preload=3D"none" =
data-mw-tmh=3D"" class=3D"mw-file-element" width=3D"250" height=3D"188" dat=
a-durationhint=3D"43" data-mwtitle=3D"The_Matrix_Bullet_Time_Effect.ogv" da=
ta-mwprovider=3D"local" resource=3D"/wiki/File:The_Matrix_Bullet_Time_Effec=
t.ogv" playsinline=3D"" disabled=3D"disabled" tabindex=3D"-1" style=3D"aspe=
ct-ratio: 250 / 188;"></video><a class=3D"mw-tmh-play" href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/File:The_Matrix_Bullet_Time_Effect.ogv" title=3D"Play vid=
eo" role=3D"button"><span class=3D"mw-tmh-play-icon notheme"></span></a><sp=
an class=3D"mw-tmh-duration mw-tmh-label"><span class=3D"sr-only">Duration:=
 43 seconds.</span><span aria-hidden=3D"true">0:43</span></span></span></sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:The_Matrix_Bullet_Time_Eff=
ect.ogv" class=3D"mw-file-magnify"></a><figcaption>The "<a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bullet_time" title=3D"Bullet time">bullet time</a>" e=
ffect was created for the film. A scene would be computer-modeled to decide=
 the positioning of the physical cameras. The actor then provided their per=
formance in a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chroma_key" title=3D=
"Chroma key">chroma key</a> setup, while the cameras were fired in rapid su=
ccession, with fractions of a second delay between each shot. The result wa=
s combined with CGI backgrounds to create the final effect at (0:33).</figc=
aption></figure>
<blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>As for artistic inspiration for bull=
et time, I would credit <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Otomo_Kats=
uhiro" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Otomo Katsuhiro">Otomo Katsuhiro</a>,=
 who co-wrote and directed <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Akir=
a_(1988_film)" title=3D"Akira (1988 film)">Akira</a></i>, which definitely =
blew me away, along with director <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Michel_Gondry" title=3D"Michel Gondry">Michel Gondry</a>. His music videos =
experimented with a different type of technique called view-morphing and it=
 was just part of the beginning of uncovering the creative approaches towar=
d using still cameras for special effects. Our technique was significantly =
different because we built it to move around objects that were themselves i=
n motion, and we were also able to create slow-motion events that 'virtual =
cameras' could move around=E2=80=94rather than the static action in Gondry'=
s music videos with limited camera moves.</p></blockquote><div class=3D"tem=
platequotecite"><p style=3D"display: inline; padding-left: 2.3em;">=E2=80=
=94=E2=80=8A<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Gaeta" title=3D"J=
ohn Gaeta">John Gaeta</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-gaeta-empire_76-0" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-gaet=
a-empire-76"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>75<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup><span style=3D"display:none" data-plural=3D"0"></sp=
an></p></div>
<p>The film is known for popularizing a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Visual_effect" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Visual effect">visual e=
ffect</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Lane_City_of_God_77-0" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-Lane_City_of_God=
-77"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>76<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> known as "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bullet_=
time" title=3D"Bullet time">bullet time</a>", which allows a <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shot_(filmmaking)" title=3D"Shot (filmmaking)">s=
hot</a> to progress in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slow_motion=
" title=3D"Slow motion">slow motion</a> while the camera appears to move th=
rough the scene at normal speed.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-guardian-sfx_78-0" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_no=
te-guardian-sfx-78"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>77<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-79" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-79"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>78<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> Bullet time has been described as "a visual analogy for privileged momen=
ts of consciousness within the Matrix",<sup id=3D"cite_ref-80" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-80"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>79<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> and throughout the film, the effect is used to illustrate charac=
ters' exertion of control over time and space.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-81" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_not=
e-81"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>80<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> The Wachowskis first imagined an action sequence that slo=
wed time while the camera pivoted rapidly around the subjects, and proposed=
 the effect in their screenplay for the film. When <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/John_Gaeta" title=3D"John Gaeta">John Gaeta</a> read the s=
cript, he pleaded with an effects producer at <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Manex_Visual_Effects" title=3D"Manex Visual Effects">Mass.Illus=
ion</a> to let him work on the project, and created a prototype that led to=
 him becoming the film's visual effects supervisor.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Wire=
d_VFX_82-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Th=
e_Matrix#cite_note-Wired_VFX-82"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>81<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-83" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_not=
e-83"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>82<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The method used for creating these effects involved a technically ex=
panded version of an old art photography technique known as time-slice phot=
ography, in which an array of cameras are placed around an object and trigg=
ered simultaneously. Each camera captures a still picture, contributing one=
 frame to the video sequence, which creates the effect of "virtual camera m=
ovement"; the illusion of a viewpoint moving around an object that appears =
frozen in time.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-guardian-sfx_78-1" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-guardian-sfx-7=
8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>77<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup>
</p><p>The bullet time effect is similar but slightly more complicated, inc=
orporating temporal motion so that rather than appearing totally frozen, th=
e scene progresses in slow and variable motion.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-gaeta-em=
pire_76-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The=
_Matrix#cite_note-gaeta-empire-76"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>75<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Wired_VFX=
_82-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Mat=
rix#cite_note-Wired_VFX-82"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>81<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The cameras' positions and exposure=
s were <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Previsualization" title=3D"=
Previsualization">previsualized</a> using a 3D simulation. Instead of firin=
g the cameras simultaneously, the visual effect team fired the cameras frac=
tions of a second after each other, so that each camera could capture the a=
ction as it progressed, creating a super slow-motion effect.<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-guardian-sfx_78-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-guardian-sfx-78"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>77<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> When the frames=
 were put together, the resulting slow-motion effects reached a <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frame_frequency" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Frame frequency">frame frequency</a> of 12,000 per second, as opposed t=
o the normal 24 frames per second of film.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Influence_Scr=
eened_33-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Th=
e_Matrix#cite_note-Influence_Screened-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Standard movie camera=
s were placed at the ends of the array to pick up the normal speed action b=
efore and after. Because the cameras circle the subject almost completely i=
n most of the sequences, computer technology was used to edit out the camer=
as that appeared in the background on the other side.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-gu=
ardian-sfx_78-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/The_Matrix#cite_note-guardian-sfx-78"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>77<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> To create backgrounds,=
 Gaeta hired George Borshukov, who created 3D models based on the geometry =
of buildings and used the photographs of the buildings themselves as textur=
e.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space=
:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_n=
eeded" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs =
references to reliable sources. (February 2024)">citation needed</span></a>=
</i>]</sup>
</p><p>The photo-realistic surroundings generated by this method were incor=
porated into the bullet time scene,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Wired_VFX_82-2" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_no=
te-Wired_VFX-82"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>81<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and algorithms based on <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Optical_flow" title=3D"Optical flow">optical flow</a> we=
re used to interpolate between the still images to produce a fluent dynamic=
 motion;<sup id=3D"cite_ref-84" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-84"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>83<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-8=
5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#=
cite_note-85"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>84<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup> the computer-generated "lead in" and "lead out" s=
lides were filled in between frames in sequence to get an illusion of orbit=
ing the scene.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-86" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-86"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>85<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Manex Visual E=
ffects used a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cluster_(computing)"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cluster (computing)">cluster</a> farm runni=
ng the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unix-like" title=3D"Unix-li=
ke">Unix-like</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Operating_system=
" title=3D"Operating system">operating system</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/FreeBSD" title=3D"FreeBSD">FreeBSD</a> to render many of th=
e film's visual effects.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-87" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-87"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>86<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-88" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-88"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>87<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Manex also handled creature effects, such as Sentinels and machines =
in real world scenes; <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Animal_Logic=
" title=3D"Animal Logic">Animal Logic</a> created the code hallway and the =
exploding Agent at the end of the film. DFilm managed scenes that required =
heavy use of digital compositing, such as Neo's jump off a skyscraper and t=
he helicopter crash into a building. The ripple effect in the latter scene =
was created digitally, but the shot also included practical elements, and m=
onths of extensive research were needed to find the correct kind of glass a=
nd explosives to use. The scene was shot by colliding a quarter-scale helic=
opter mock-up into a glass wall wired to concentric rings of explosives; th=
e explosives were then triggered in sequence from the center outward, to cr=
eate a wave of exploding glass.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Post-production_89-0" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_=
note-Post-production-89"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>88<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Photogrammetry" title=
=3D"Photogrammetry">photogrammetric</a> and image-based <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer-generated_imagery" title=3D"Computer-generat=
ed imagery">computer-generated</a> background approaches in <i>The Matrix</=
i><span class=3D"nowrap" style=3D"padding-left:0.1em;">'</span>s bullet tim=
e evolved into innovations unveiled in the sequels <i><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix_Reloaded" title=3D"The Matrix Reloaded">The =
Matrix Reloaded</a></i> and <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The=
_Matrix_Revolutions" title=3D"The Matrix Revolutions">The Matrix Revolution=
s</a></i>. The method of using real photographs of buildings as texture for=
 3D models eventually led the visual effect team to digitize all data, such=
 as scenes, characters' motions and expressions. It also led to the develop=
ment of "Universal Capture", a process which samples and stores facial deta=
ils and expressions at high resolution. With these highly detailed collecte=
d data, the team were able to create virtual cinematography in which charac=
ters, locations and events can all be created digitally and viewed through =
virtual cameras, eliminating the restrictions of real cameras.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-Wired_VFX_82-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-Wired_VFX-82"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>81<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Release">Release</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
