aking special effects". Some have described <i>The Matrix</i> as one of the=
 best <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Science_fiction_film" title=
=3D"Science fiction film">science fiction films</a> of all time;<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-heritage1_9-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-heritage1-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-a=
utogenerated1_10-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-autogenerated1-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <i><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Entertainment_Weekly" title=3D"Entertainment Week=
ly">Entertainment Weekly</a></i> called <i>The Matrix</i> "the most influen=
tial action movie of the generation".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Influence_EW2_23-1=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#c=
ite_note-Influence_EW2-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> There have also been those, includin=
g philosopher <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Irwin_(philo=
sopher)" title=3D"William Irwin (philosopher)">William Irwin</a>, who have =
suggested that the film explores significant philosophical and spiritual th=
emes. On <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Review_aggregator" title=
=3D"Review aggregator">review aggregator</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Rotten_Tomatoes" title=3D"Rotten Tomatoes">Rotten Tomatoes</a>, =
the film holds an approval rating of 83% based on 210 reviews, with an aver=
age score of 7.7/10. The site's critical consensus reads, "Thanks to the Wa=
chowskis' imaginative vision, <i>The Matrix</i> is a smartly crafted combin=
ation of spectacular action and groundbreaking special effects".<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-RottenTomatoes_7-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-RottenTomatoes-7"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> At <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metacritic" title=3D"Metacritic">Metacrit=
ic</a>, which assigns a rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critic=
s, the film received a score of 73 based on 35 reviews, indicating "general=
ly favorable reviews".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-meta_8-2" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-meta-8"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> Audiences polled by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CinemaScore=
" title=3D"CinemaScore">CinemaScore</a> gave the film an average grade of "=
A=E2=88=92" on an A+ to F scale.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-CinemaScore_116-0" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_no=
te-CinemaScore-116"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>115<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> It ranked 323rd among critics, and 546th a=
mong directors, in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Sight_%=
26_Sound_Top_50_Greatest_Films_of_All_Time" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
The Sight &amp; Sound Top 50 Greatest Films of All Time">2012 <i>Sight &amp=
; Sound</i> polls of the greatest films ever made</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1=
17" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix=
#cite_note-117"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>116<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Philip Strick commented in <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Sight_%26_Sound" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sight &amp; Sound">Sight=
 &amp; Sound</a></i>, if the Wachowskis "claim no originality of message, t=
hey are startling innovators of method," praising the film's details and it=
s "broadside of astonishing images".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-sightandsound_118-0=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#c=
ite_note-sightandsound-118"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>117<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Roger_Ebert" title=3D"Roger Ebert">Roger Ebert</a> gave the film thr=
ee stars out of four: he praised the film's visuals and premise, but dislik=
ed the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Three-act_structure" title=
=3D"Three-act structure">third act</a>'s focus on action.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-rogerebert_119-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-rogerebert-119"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>118<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Similarly, <i><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Time_Out_Group" title=3D"Time Out Group=
">Time Out</a></i> praised the "entertainingly ingenious" switches between =
different realities, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hugo_Weaving"=
 title=3D"Hugo Weaving">Hugo Weaving</a>'s "engagingly odd" performance, an=
d the film's cinematography and production design, but concluded, "the prom=
ising premise is steadily wasted as the film turns into a fairly routine ac=
tion pic&nbsp;... yet another slice of overlong, high-concept hokum."<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-timeout_120-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-timeout-120"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>119<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jonathan_Rosenbaum" title=
=3D"Jonathan Rosenbaum">Jonathan Rosenbaum</a> of the <i><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chicago_Reader" title=3D"Chicago Reader">Chicago Rea=
der</a></i> reviewed the film negatively, criticizing it as "simpleminded f=
un for roughly the first hour, until the movie becomes overwhelmed by its m=
any sources ... There's not much humor to keep it all life-size, and by the=
 final stretch it's become bloated, mechanical, and tiresome."<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-Rosenbaum_review_121-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-Rosenbaum_review-121"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>120<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Ian Nathan of <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Empire_(ma=
gazine)" title=3D"Empire (magazine)">Empire</a></i> described Carrie-Anne M=
oss as "a major find", praised the "surreal visual highs" enabled by the bu=
llet time (or "flo-mo") effect, and described the film as "technically mind=
-blowing, style merged perfectly with content and just so damn cool". Natha=
n remarked that although the film's "looney plot" would not stand up to scr=
utiny, that was not a big flaw because "<i>The Matrix</i> is about pure exp=
erience".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Empire_review_122-0" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-Empire_review-122"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>121<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maitland_McDonagh" t=
itle=3D"Maitland McDonagh">Maitland McDonagh</a> said in her review for <i>=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/TV_Guide" title=3D"TV Guide">TV Gu=
ide</a></i>, the Wachowskis' "through-the-looking-glass plot... manages to =
work surprisingly well on a number of levels: as a dystopian sci-fi thrille=
r, as a brilliant excuse for the film's lavish and hyperkinetic fight scene=
s, and as a pretty compelling call to the dead-above-the-eyeballs masses to=
 unite and cast off their chains... This dazzling pop allegory is steeped i=
n a dark, pulpy sensibility that transcends nostalgic pastiche and stands f=
irmly on its own merits."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-TV_Guide_review_123-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_not=
e-TV_Guide_review-123"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>122<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Salon_(website)" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Salon (website)">Salon</a></i><span class=3D"nowr=
ap" style=3D"padding-left:0.1em;">'</span>s reviewer Andrew O'Hehir acknowl=
edged that although <i>The Matrix</i> is in his view a fundamentally immatu=
re and unoriginal film ("It lacks anything like adult emotion... all this p=
seudo-spiritual hokum, along with the over-ramped onslaught of special effe=
cts=E2=80=94some of them quite amazing=E2=80=94will hold 14-year-old boys i=
n rapture, not to mention those of us of all ages and genders who still har=
bor a 14-year-old boy somewhere inside"), he concluded, "as in <i><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bound_(1996_film)" title=3D"Bound (1996 f=
ilm)">Bound</a></i>, there's an appealing scope and daring to the Wachowski=
s' work, and their eagerness for more plot twists and more crazy images bec=
omes increasingly infectious. In a limited and profoundly geeky sense, this=
 might be an important and generous film. The Wachowskis have little feelin=
g for character or human interaction, but their passion for <i>movies</i>=
=E2=80=94for making them, watching them, inhabiting their world=E2=80=94is =
pure and deep."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Salon_review_124-0" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-Salon_review-=
124"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>123<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Filmmakers and science fiction creators alike generally took a compl=
imentary perspective of <i>The Matrix</i>. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/William_Gibson" title=3D"William Gibson">William Gibson</a>, a key=
 figure in cyberpunk fiction, called the film "an innocent delight I hadn't=
 felt in a long time", and stated, "Neo is my favourite-ever science fictio=
n hero, absolutely."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-125" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-125"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>124<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joss_Whedon" title=3D"Joss Whedon">Joss=
 Whedon</a> called the film "my number one" and praised its storytelling, s=
tructure and depth, concluding, "It works on whatever level you want to bri=
ng to it".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-126" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-126"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>125<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Darren_Aronofsky" title=3D"Darren Aronofsky">Darr=
en Aronofsky</a> commented, "I walked out of <i>The Matrix</i>&nbsp;... and=
 I was thinking, 'What kind of science fiction movie can people make now?' =
The Wachowskis basically took all the great sci-fi ideas of the 20th centur=
y and rolled them into a delicious pop culture sandwich that everyone on th=
e planet devoured."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Aronofsky:_127-0" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-Aronofsky:-=
127"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>126<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M._Night_Shyamal=
an" title=3D"M. Night Shyamalan">M. Night Shyamalan</a> expressed admiratio=
n for the Wachowskis, stating, "Whatever you think of <i>The Matrix</i>, ev=
ery shot is there because of the passion they have! You can see they argued=
 it out!".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Shyamalan:_128-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-Shyamalan:-128"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>127<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simon_Pegg" title=3D"Simo=
n Pegg">Simon Pegg</a> said that <i>The Matrix</i> provided "the excitement=
 and satisfaction that <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Phan=
tom_Menace" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"The Phantom Menace">The Phantom =
Menace</a></i> failed to inspire. <i>The Matrix</i> seemed fresh and cool a=
nd visually breathtaking; making wonderful, intelligent use of CGI to augme=
nt the on-screen action, striking a perfect balance of the real and the hyp=
erreal. It was possibly the coolest film I had ever seen."<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-simonpegg_129-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-simonpegg-129"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>128<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quentin_Tarantino" title=3D"Quentin Tarantino">Quentin=
 Tarantino</a> counted <i>The Matrix</i> as one of his twenty favorite movi=
es from 1992 to 2009.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Tarantino:_130-0" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-Tarantino=
:-130"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>129<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Cameron"=
 title=3D"James Cameron">James Cameron</a> called it "one of the most profo=
undly fresh science fiction films ever made".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-131" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_not=
e-131"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>130<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christopher_No=
lan" title=3D"Christopher Nolan">Christopher Nolan</a> described it as "an =
incredibly palpable mainstream phenomenon that made people think, Hey, what=
 if this isn't real?"<sup id=3D"cite_ref-132" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix#cite_note-132"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>131<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
